  "prompt": "Which songs are best for shrilled voice?",
  "response": "If you have a shrill voice and are looking for songs that complement or showcase its unique qualities, consider the following genres and specific songs that might work well:\n\n### Pop Songs\n1. **\"Call Me Maybe\" by Carly Rae Jepsen** - Catchy and playful, it can work well with a higher pitch.\n2. **\"Teenage Dream\" by Katy Perry** - Upbeat and fun, perfect for a higher vocal range.\n3. **\"Rolling in the Deep\" by Adele** - While Adele's voice is known for its depth, the powerful chorus can be showcased with a shriller tone.\n4. **\"Stay\" by Rihanna feat. Mikky Ekko** - The emotional delivery can highlight a shrill voice effectively.\n\n### Musical Theatre\n1. **\"Popular\" from Wicked** - A fun, sassy song that benefits from a higher vocal quality.\n2. **\"Adele Dazeem\" from Frozen** - The playful nature of the song allows for a higher range.\n3. **\"Defying Gravity\" from Wicked** - While challenging, it can work well with a strong, shrill delivery.\n\n### Classic Rock\n1. **\"Barracuda\" by Heart** - A powerful rock anthem that can really show off a shrill voice in the chorus.\n2. **\"Dreams\" by Fleetwood Mac** - The higher harmonies can complement a shrill voice well.\n\n### Indie/Alternative\n1. **\"Dog Days Are Over\" by Florence + the Machine** - The dynamic shifts allow for showcasing a higher vocal quality.\n2. **\"Home\" by Edward Sharpe & The Magnetic Zeros** - A fun and upbeat song that can be sung playfully.\n\n### R&B/Soul\n1. **\"Back to Black\" by Amy Winehouse** - The emotional depth of the song can work with a higher pitch.\n \n### Tips:\n- Look for songs that allow for emotional expression, as a shrill voice can often convey a lot of feeling.\n- Consider songs in a higher key, as they often work better with a shriller voice.\n\nAlways choose songs that you feel comfortable with and that allow you to showcase your voice in the best way possible!",
